				\begin{document}$$0\nu \beta \beta $$\end{document}0νββ) is a hypothetical nuclear transition \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$A \Longrightarrow (A-2) + 2 e^{-}$$\end{document}A⟹(A-2)+2e- that shares the full decay-energy between the daughter nucleus and the two electrons, without emission of electron anti-neutrinos. It violates lepton number by two units and would constitute clear evidence of physics beyond the standard model. The observation of this decay was first proposed by Furry in 1939 [1], two years after Ettore Majorana pointed out that the neutrino, being a neutral lepton, could be described by a real valued wave function as solution of a Hermitian form of the Dirac equation. This in turn implies that these solutions are identical to the solutions for their anti-particles [2]. As a massive particle this Majorana neutrino would interact both as a left-handed particle and a right-handed anti-particle. Consequently it would allow for a double beta decay process without emission of neutrinos in addition to the standard-model-allowed double beta decay process with emission of two neutrinos [3]. Beyond this so called mass mechanism several other standard model extensions provide lepton number violating mechanisms [4–8] that can be tested through neutrinoless double beta decay searches. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$0\nu \beta \beta $$\end{document}0νββ is hence a crucial probe that complements direct [9, 10] and indirect neutrino mass measurements [11]. It is uniquely placed to answer the question if there is a Majorana neutrino mass and if neutrinos may have contributed to the generation of the matter–antimatter asymmetry in the early Universe [12].

